---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro'
import SiteCta from '../components/SiteCta.astro'

const title = 'Connect Veqtor MCP to Claude Desktop or Claude Code'
const description = 'Install the current public Veqtor 0.1.2 package for Claude Code or manual Claude Desktop setup, and check the publication status of the v0.3.0 Desktop Extension candidate.'
const releasesUrl = 'https://github.com/JohnDeer-ai/veqtor-mcp/releases'
const desktopServerEntry = `"veqtor": {
  "command": "/absolute/path/to/uvx",
  "args": ["veqtor-mcp@0.1.2"]
}`

const desktopServersProperty = `"mcpServers": {
  "veqtor": {
    "command": "/absolute/path/to/uvx",
    "args": ["veqtor-mcp@0.1.2"]
  }
}`

const freshDesktopConfig = `{
  "mcpServers": {
    "veqtor": {
      "command": "/absolute/path/to/uvx",
      "args": ["veqtor-mcp@0.1.2"]
    }
  }
}`

const desktopAuthorSetting = `"env": {
  "VEQTOR_TRACKED_CHANGE_AUTHOR": "Alex Morgan"
}`
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/setup">
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Connect"
    title="Connect Veqtor to Claude."
    lede="The current public release is 0.1.2 on PyPI with matching immutable GitHub artifacts. The v0.3.0 macOS extension is still a release candidate, not a public download."
    meta="Public v0.1.2 · v0.3.0 release candidate · macOS and Linux"
    breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Connect' }]}
  />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell setup-layout">
      <aside class="setup-nav" aria-label="Connection options">
        <strong>Choose your app</strong>
        <a href="#claude-desktop">Claude Desktop on Mac</a>
        <a href="#claude-code">Claude Code</a>
        <a href="#desktop-manual">Manual Desktop fallback</a>
        <a href="#verify">Verify with sample documents</a>
        <a href="#troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</a>
      </aside>

      <div class="prose setup-content">
        <section id="before-you-start">
          <p class="eyebrow">Before you start</p>
          <h2>What you need</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>A Mac or Linux computer.</li>
            <li>Claude Code on Mac or Linux, or Claude Desktop on a Mac.</li>
            <li>For the future Desktop extension: Claude Desktop on a Mac. The public MCPB is not available yet.</li>
            <li>For the current public Claude Code or Desktop setup: <a href="https://docs.astral.sh/uv/getting-started/installation/">uv installed</a>.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="notice"><strong>v0.3.0 is not public yet.</strong><p>A package version in source or a CI artifact is not a release. The macOS MCPB becomes installable only after clean-Mac acceptance, public PyPI verification and immutable GitHub Release publication all succeed for the same candidate.</p></div>
          <div class="notice"><strong>Windows is not supported in the public Alpha.</strong><p>Do not improvise a Windows installation for real matters; the current local record locking and release tests target Mac and Linux.</p></div>
        </section>

        <section id="claude-desktop">
          <p class="eyebrow">Release-candidate status</p>
          <h2>Claude Desktop Extension for Mac</h2>
          <p>The v0.3.0 candidate packages the local server, its exact dependency lock and four synthetic Word rounds into one macOS extension. It still processes documents locally; the extension does not create a Veqtor account or upload your files to a Veqtor service.</p>
          <div class="notice"><strong>There is no official v0.3.0 download yet.</strong><p>Do not guess a release-asset URL or install an MCPB copied from CI, a branch, chat, issue or unrelated site. Publication must follow the exact release workflow; the source tree cannot declare itself immutable.</p></div>
          <p><a class="button button--secondary" href={releasesUrl}>Check official GitHub Releases ↗</a></p>
          <p>After v0.3.0 appears in that release list with the exact MCPB and checksum manifest:</p>
          <ol>
            <li>Download the file ending in <code>-macos.mcpb</code> from that official release.</li>
            <li>Open it and approve installation in Claude Desktop.</li>
            <li>Enter the name that Word should show as the author of new tracked changes.</li>
            <li>Open Claude Desktop's extension settings. Make sure Veqtor is enabled and its local server shows as connected. If it does not connect, fully quit and reopen Claude Desktop.</li>
            <li>Open a new chat and run the bundled <strong>try_veqtor_demo</strong> prompt.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>After publication, the first start may download a compatible Python runtime and the dependencies pinned in the extension. Later starts can use the local host cache.</p>
          <h3>First prompt</h3>
          <blockquote>Using the Veqtor tools, what happened to the limitation of liability across the four Word rounds in the folder named demo? Start with list_rounds, use inspect_document for a hash-bound paragraph reference, then use map_rounds to compare that evidence across the folder. Keep tool-confirmed document facts separate from your interpretation, and do not treat filename order as verified chronology or lineage.</blockquote>
          <p>The bundled prompt is read-only. For a write test, first copy the four synthetic DOCX files to a new writable folder outside the installed extension and create the output only in that copy. After apply, ask Claude to list the folder again and re-extract the output; the source hash should stay unchanged and the output hash should agree across apply, list and extraction.</p>
          <h3>Optional advanced integrity check</h3>
          <p>After promotion, the ordinary path will be to download from the official immutable GitHub Release and open the extension. Advanced users can also download <code>SHA256SUMS.txt</code>, run the commands below and compare the two values. The future public artifact will be checksum-bound but not digitally signed.</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Terminal · optional</span><span>SHA-256</span></div><pre><code>{`shasum -a 256 veqtor-mcp-0.3.0-macos.mcpb
grep ' veqtor-mcp-0.3.0-macos.mcpb$' SHA256SUMS.txt`}</code></pre></div>
          <h3>Remove or reinstall</h3>
          <p>Once published, uninstall Veqtor from Claude Desktop's extension settings. The first public MCPB has no older extension to roll back to; before promotion its gate covers a clean Mac without a manually installed uv or Python, all eight tools, uninstall, confirmation that the tools disappear, and reinstall of the same artifact. Real upgrade and rollback become required for the next extension release.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="claude-code">
          <p class="eyebrow">Option A</p>
          <h2>Claude Code on Mac or Linux</h2>
          <p>Register the exact current public version from PyPI for your user account:</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Terminal</span><span>Public v0.1.2</span></div><pre><code>claude mcp add --transport stdio --scope user veqtor -- uvx veqtor-mcp@0.1.2</code></pre></div>
          <p>Then confirm that Claude Code can see the registration:</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Terminal</span><span>Verify</span></div><pre><code>claude mcp get veqtor</code></pre></div>
          <p>Open a new Claude Code session after registering Veqtor. The user scope keeps this private local connection available across your projects on this computer. It does not make Veqtor a network service.</p>
          <h3>Set the author shown in new tracked changes</h3>
          <p>If you want Word to show your name as the author of new changes, register the server with this environment setting. Replace <code>Your Name</code> with your actual name:</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Terminal</span><span>Optional · public v0.1.2</span></div><pre><code>{`claude mcp add --transport stdio --scope user veqtor \
  -e VEQTOR_TRACKED_CHANGE_AUTHOR="Your Name" -- \
  uvx veqtor-mcp@0.1.2`}</code></pre></div>
          <p>If you do not set a name, Word will show <code>Veqtor MCP</code>. The author is fixed when the server starts and Claude cannot change it for an individual edit.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="desktop-manual">
          <p class="eyebrow">Current public fallback</p>
          <h2>Manual Claude Desktop setup</h2>
          <p>This path uses the exact public PyPI version 0.1.2. Matching wheel, sdist and checksum artifacts remain available from the immutable GitHub v0.1.2 release while the v0.3.0 Desktop Extension completes its separate release gate.</p>
          <p>Desktop apps may not see the same terminal paths as your shell. First find the full path to <code>uvx</code>:</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Terminal</span><span>Find uvx</span></div><pre><code>command -v uvx</code></pre></div>
          <p>In Claude Desktop, open <strong>Settings → Developer → Edit Config</strong>. This opens <code>~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json</code>.</p>
          <div class="notice"><strong>Back up the file before editing it.</strong><p>Duplicate it in Finder and keep the copy until the connection works. If the file already contains other servers or settings, preserve them. Do not replace the whole file with the examples below.</p></div>
          <h3>If your file already contains <code>mcpServers</code></h3>
          <p>Add only the <code>veqtor</code> entry inside the existing <code>mcpServers</code> object. Keep every other server and every setting outside that object. JSON entries next to each other need a comma between them.</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Entry to add inside mcpServers</span><span>Preserve existing entries</span></div><pre><code set:text={desktopServerEntry}></code></pre></div>
          <h3>If the file has other settings but no <code>mcpServers</code></h3>
          <p>Add this property inside the file's outermost braces, alongside the existing root-level settings. Keep those settings and add a comma between adjacent root properties.</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Root property to add</span><span>Preserve existing settings</span></div><pre><code set:text={desktopServersProperty}></code></pre></div>
          <h3>If the file is empty</h3>
          <p>Use this complete configuration. In either example, replace <code>/absolute/path/to/uvx</code> with the result from <code>command -v uvx</code>.</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>claude_desktop_config.json</span><span>New configuration only</span></div><pre><code set:text={freshDesktopConfig}></code></pre></div>
          <h3>Choose the author shown in new tracked changes</h3>
          <p>The examples above use the default author, <code>Veqtor MCP</code>. To show your own name in Word, add this <code>env</code> setting inside the <code>veqtor</code> entry, after the <code>args</code> line. Add a comma after the <code>args</code> line, and replace <code>Alex Morgan</code> with your actual name. Do not leave the example name in your configuration.</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Optional author setting</span><span>Replace the example name</span></div><pre><code set:text={desktopAuthorSetting}></code></pre></div>
          <p>Quit Claude Desktop fully and reopen it after changing the executable, version or author name.</p>
          <h3>Confirm the Claude Desktop connection</h3>
          <p>Start a new chat, click the <strong>+</strong> button beside the message box, then open <strong>Connectors</strong>. Veqtor should appear with its tools. You can also open <strong>Settings → Developer</strong> to see its connection status and logs. The <code>claude mcp get veqtor</code> command checks Claude Code only; it does not verify this Desktop configuration.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="verify">
          <p class="eyebrow">First run</p>
          <h2>Verify the connection with sample documents</h2>
          <p>Create a fresh, disposable four-round negotiation:</p>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Terminal</span><span>Public v0.1.2</span></div><pre><code>uvx --from "veqtor-mcp==0.1.2" veqtor-demo-rounds ~/veqtor-demo-rounds</code></pre></div>
          <p>In a new Claude session, ask:</p>
          <blockquote>Using the Veqtor tools, what happened to the limitation of liability across the rounds in ~/veqtor-demo-rounds?</blockquote>
          <p>If Claude identifies and explains the four rounds, the connection is working. Continue with the <a href="/demo">recorded demo</a> before trying a write workflow.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="troubleshooting">
          <p class="eyebrow">Troubleshooting</p>
          <h2>Common setup problems</h2>
          <h3>Claude Code does not show Veqtor</h3>
          <p>Run <code>claude mcp get veqtor</code> in Terminal. If the registration appears, close the current Claude Code session and start a new one.</p>
          <h3>Claude Desktop does not show Veqtor</h3>
          <p>Open Claude Desktop's extension settings and confirm that Veqtor is enabled and connected. If it is enabled but not connected, fully quit and reopen Claude Desktop. Then check <strong>+ → Connectors</strong> in a new chat. For the manual JSON fallback, open <strong>Settings → Developer</strong> to inspect the connection status and server logs. Do not use <code>claude mcp get veqtor</code> for this check; it reads Claude Code registrations, not Desktop extensions or <code>claude_desktop_config.json</code>.</p>
          <h3>Claude Desktop stopped showing another server</h3>
          <p>Restore your backup, then add only the <code>veqtor</code> entry inside its existing <code>mcpServers</code> object. Preserve all other entries and root-level settings, and check the commas between JSON entries.</p>
          <h3>Claude Desktop cannot start the server</h3>
          <p>Use the absolute path returned by <code>command -v uvx</code>. Do not assume the desktop app inherits your shell path.</p>
          <h3>Run local diagnostics</h3>
          <div class="code-block"><div class="code-block__head"><span>Terminal</span><span>Public v0.1.2</span></div><pre><code>uvx veqtor-mcp@0.1.2 doctor</code></pre></div>
          <h3>Still blocked?</h3>
          <p>Search or open a <a href="https://github.com/JohnDeer-ai/veqtor-mcp/issues">GitHub Issue</a> using synthetic files only. Never post client wording, local paths, credentials or local activity records.</p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <SiteCta title="Connection working? Learn the complete review sequence." primaryHref="/demo" primaryLabel="Watch the demo" secondaryHref="/docs" secondaryLabel="Open the docs" />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .setup-layout { display: grid; gap: clamp(40px, 8vw, 100px); grid-template-columns: minmax(210px, .32fr) minmax(0, 1fr); }
  .setup-nav, .setup-content { min-width: 0; }
  .setup-content .code-block { max-width: 100%; }
  .setup-nav { align-self: start; border-top: 1px solid var(--line-strong); position: sticky; top: 104px; }
  .setup-nav strong, .setup-nav a { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); display: block; padding: 14px 0; }
  .setup-nav strong { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: var(--type-micro); font-weight: var(--weight-label); letter-spacing: .07em; text-transform: uppercase; }
  .setup-nav a { color: var(--muted); font-size: 13px; text-decoration: none; }
  .setup-nav a:hover { color: var(--ink); }
  .setup-content section + section { border-top: 1px solid var(--line); margin-top: 70px; padding-top: 64px; }
  @media (max-width: 760px) { .setup-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr); } .setup-nav { position: static; } }
</style>
